        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Purpose</title>
            <para>Visual inspection of the engine for possible hard or no start conditions.</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Test Procedure</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect fuel tank and lines for damage and leaks.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check oil line from high pressure pump to oil supply manifold for oil leaks.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect entire cooling system for leaks.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check air induction system for leaks. Refer to Air Induction System Inspection and
                    Pressure Test .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect engine wiring harness for correct routing and protection against rubbing or
                    chaffing. Inspect for connected CMP and IPR.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Engine will not start with IPR or CMP disconnected</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check sensor, relay, and control module connections.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">All connections must be seated, in good condition, and free from damage or corrosion.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury, do not under any circumstances allow smoking, an electric spark or
                        open flame near the battery or explosion may occur.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect battery cable and fuse battery connections for corrosion.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>ECM harness connections must be torqued to 50 in&#183;lb (5.65 N&#183;m).</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Possible Causes for Hard or No Start Conditions.</title>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Loose or leaking fuel supply lines could cause fuel system to lose prime.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Kinked or blocked fuel supply lines will restrict fuel flow.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Excessive fuel or oil leaks.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Engine coolant leaks may indicate serious engine problems.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Damaged or incorrectly installed electronic connectors.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The Camshaft Position Sensor (CMP) and Injection Pressure Regulator valve (IPR) are the most
                        critical electronic components to inspect if the engine fails to start.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="p1750202">
            <title>Air Induction System Inspection</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect air cleaner housing for damage or distortion that could allow unfiltered air
                    into the engine.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Unfiltered air will cause accelerated engine wear.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect for end seal movement inside the housing. End seal movement is indicated if the
                    seal contact area is polished. A polished contact area indicates that unfiltered air has passed by
                    the filter element and into the engine.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect air cleaner element for end cap dents, holes, damaged seals, and soot.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect air intake hoses and clamps for tightness and positioning over sealing beads.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the chassis mounted charge air cooler and piping.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Air Induction System Pressure Test</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mask the outer diameter of air cleaner air inlet with duct tape and plug air cleaner
                    canister drain.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the air cleaner restriction indicator or tubing to the air cleaner. Install a
                    plug to seal the opening.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Find the cold air discharge pipe containing a plug. Remove the plug and connect a
                    manually regulated air supply with a pressure gauge refer to Regulated Air Supply .
                </para>
                <figure id="f1750203" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figeg1/EG1177.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
                    <caption>Regulated Air Supply</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply 5 -8 psi of air pressure to the air induction system. A constant air supply is
                    needed to replace air lost through opened intake valves.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Coat areas
                    <emph type="bold">a</emph>
                    through
                    <emph type="bold">f</emph>listed below with a soap solution and check for leaks: refer to Air
                    Induction System Leakage .
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Air cleaner body surface around the outlet pipe.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Air cleaner outlet pipe to air cleaner body junction.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">All clamped hose and gasket connections between air cleaner outlet and intake
                        manifold / valve cover. This includes turbocharger connections.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1750204" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../figeg1/EG1181.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                        <caption>Checking For Air Induction System Leakage</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Surface of all air induction piping and hoses between air cleaner and intake
                        manifold / valve cover.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Air compressor air inlet piping from the air cleaner tube to and including the
                        fitting and the gasket.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Piping to the air charge cooler.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Leakage is not permitted between air cleaner and turbocharger (suction side). If leaks
                    are found, tighten hose clamps. If leaks continue, replace all parts as necessary. Retest corrected
                    area.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Air induction leaks could indicate dirt in the engine. Dirt can cause pistons rings to
                            wear or break causing high oil consumption and excessive blue smoke and pitting or erosion
                            of the turbocharger compressor wheel. If leaks are found, test crankcase pressure.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Tools Required</title>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Inspection Lamp</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Air Pressure Regulator</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Soap Solution</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcsubproc>
